******
[2] Commentary: Papua New Guinea, T Jacob John
Date: Thu 13 Sep 2018 10:29 PM
From: TJ John <tjacobjohn@yahoo.co.in>


Subject: PRO/EDR> Poliomyelitis update (41): Papua New Guinea 20180912.6025528
------------
Outbreaks of cVDPV1 have been extremely rare: in 2000, there was one in Hispaniola Island; in 2005, there was one in Madura Island in Indonesia; and now [there is an outbreak] in PNG. You have rightly pointed out that the risk factors are low type 1 population immunity due to insufficient b-OPV [bivalent oral poliovirus vaccine] coverage and the continued exposure to Sabin [OPV] type 1 virus in the bOPV. Why large islands are vulnerable remains a mystery.

I wish to speculate: the very wide circulation of cVDPV1 in PNG, with cases in Morobe (3), East Highlands (2), Enga (2), Madang (2), and National capital district (1) suggests contagious spread of the virus and not merely faecal-oral. Perhaps one of the reasons why Sabin 1 becomes cVDPV1 may be its rare ability to spread by person-to-person contact rather than ingestion as for vaccine inoculation. We know that wild polioviruses are highly contagious.

One case of polio with wild type 1 poliovirus occurs in 160-200 infected susceptible children; cVDPV1 has far lower neurovirulence, and a case may occur in 1600-2000 (or more) infected susceptible children. Thus, we can imagine the magnitude of the outbreak in terms of children infected. If only non-immune (hence, susceptible) children were to spread the virus, this magnitude of outbreak is difficult to imagine; thus, immune individuals -- including adults -- may also be participating in transmission. This is a known phenomenon.

The outbreak will soon cease, due mainly to widespread immunity provided by the cVDPV1 outbreak itself saturating the susceptible population, topped up by bOPV or mOPV1 [monovalent OPV1] campaigns. Eventually the world will have to discontinue all OPVs and use only the non-infectious inactivated polio vaccine in order to secure a totally polio-free world.

--
T Jacob John
Retired Prof. of Clinical Virology, Christian Medical College, Vellore, India
<tjacobjohn@yahoo.co.in>

[ProMED-mail would like to thank Prof. Dr. T Jacob John for this excellent discussion regarding the cVDPV1 outbreak ongoing in Papua New Guinea.

I'd like to add that if one looks at the WHO / GPEI data for cVDPV confirmed cases, since 2000, there have been a total of 115 cases of polio associated with cVDPV1, 819 cases of polio associated with cVDPV2, and 15 cases of polio associated with cVDPV3 (http://polioeradication.org/polio-today/polio-now/this-week/circulating-vaccine-derived-poliovirus/). Additional outbreaks of cVDPV1 were reported from Laos in 2015-2016 and in Madagascar in 2014-2015.

Prof. Dr. T Jacob John's last sentence summarizes the situation beautifully: "Eventually the world will have to discontinue all OPVs and use only the non-infectious inactivated polio vaccine in order to secure a totally polio-free world." - Mod.MPP]
